Overview
- This minimal Android app listens for incoming SMS and forwards the sender and body to the VISIONS Pi at /incoming_sms with header X-VISIONS-AUTH.
- Configure Pi URL and token inside the app (MainActivity) and enable forwarding.

Install & build
1. Open Android Studio.
2. Create a new project (Empty Activity) or import these files into `app/src/main/...`.
3. Replace the package name if needed (update Manifest and Kotlin package statements).
4. Add the dependencies (OkHttp, coroutines) to module build.gradle and sync.
5. Connect device (USB + adb) or use emulator (emulator can't receive SMS from carrier; you can simulate with `adb emu sms send <from> <message>`).
6. Run the app.

Permissions & testing
- On first run click "Request RECEIVE_SMS Permission" to grant the RECEIVE_SMS runtime permission.
- Set Pi URL (e.g., http://192.168.1.100:5000) and token (INCOMING_AUTH_TOKEN) then Save.
- Ensure phone is on same Wi-Fi as Pi (or Pi reachable over the network).
- Send an SMS to the phone from another phone. The app should forward automatically (or use adb to simulate: `adb emu sms send 15551234567 "Test"` on emulator).
- On the Pi check `visions_log.csv` for incoming_sms_forwarded events and check server logs.

Example curl (simulate forwarding from phone):
  curl -X POST "http://<PI_IP>:5000/incoming_sms" \
    -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
    -H "X-VISIONS-AUTH: <token>" \
    -d '{"from":"+15551234567","body":"Hi"}'

Notes & next steps
- For greater reliability use WorkManager retries, persist unsent forwards and retry later.
- Consider TLS (HTTPS) or VPN when posting over the internet.
- For full blocking features or to auto-reply from phone rather than Twilio, implement additional endpoints (e.g., server tells phone to auto-reply and phone app sends SMS).
- On some phones you may need to whitelist the app from battery optimization or enable auto-start to ensure the receiver works reliably.
